{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/influence-models-of-radicalization-on-social-media-a762fbc35c36", "time": 1682993400.3260238, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/influence-models-of-radicalization-on-social-media-a762fbc35c36/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Influence Models of Radicalization on Social Media | by Marco Brambilla | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Influence Models of Radicalization on Social Media", "description": "Considering the current trends in radical thinking and radicalism, it\u2019s crucial to understand how radicalization works on online social networks. A data science project studied the radicalization\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://dl.acm.org/citation.cfm?id=3201082", "anchor_text": "radicalization influence", "paragraph_index": 1}, {"url": "https://dl.acm.org/citation.cfm?id=3201082", "anchor_text": "radicalization influence", "paragraph_index": 7}, {"url": "https://websci18.webscience.org/", "anchor_text": "Web Science conference 2018", "paragraph_index": 7}, {"url": "http://kmi.open.ac.uk/people/member/miriam-fernandez", "anchor_text": "Miriam Fernandez", "paragraph_index": 7}, {"url": "https://dl.acm.org/citation.cfm?id=3201082", "anchor_text": "full article about this study is available online", "paragraph_index": 8}], "all_paragraphs": ["Considering the current trends in radical thinking and radicalism, it\u2019s crucial to understand how radicalization works on online social networks.", "A data science project studied the radicalization influence problem, based on the \u201croots of radicalization\u201d model taken from social science models. The work revolved around three levels that have been considered for influence:", "Radicalization has been studied by analyzing radical speech style (n-gram model), and people have been compared to that through cosine similarity for the language.", "A dataset is available on Kaggle for this, containing 112 general (non-radicalized) users and 112 pro-ISIS radicalized users.", "The first analysis is about classification of radical and non-radical users, based on personal and social (meso level). Results show that the two aspects are quite correlated:", "Users can thus be rather easily classified in the two categories, even with pretty simple classifiers. Naive-Bayes classification already reached 90% precision.", "The second analysis looked into prediction of radicalization in time. To do that, the users\u2019 timelines were split in two time-dependent sets, the first 80% of the post are used training and the newest 20% for testing. As a result, for radicalization prediction the precision is higher for the neutral user group, and recall is higher for the pro-ISIS radical group. In both cases, precision and recall were not extremely high. This is possibly due to the possible flexibility that should be considered in the time window for radicalization. Further studies can therefore be applied to improve the detection of this phenomenon.", "This study on radicalization influence has been presented at the Web Science conference 2018 in Amstedam by Miriam Fernandez, Moizzah Asif, Harith Alani (Open University, KMI, UK).", "The full article about this study is available online.", "The paper has been assigned the best paper award at WebSci2018!", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "Data science, social and media analysis. Data, software and models all around."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2Fa762fbc35c36&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Finfluence-models-of-radicalization-on-social-media-a762fbc35c36&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "